INSERT INTO blog_posts (title, slug, excerpt, content, category, published, published_at, seo_title, seo_description) VALUES
(
  'Logo Design Pricing in Lagos: What to Actually Expect',
  'logo-design-pricing-lagos-what-to-expect',
  'Thinking about getting a logo done in Lagos and confused by the price range you are seeing online? Here is an honest breakdown of what affects cost and what you should actually expect to pay.',
  E'One of the most common questions I get before a project even starts is simple: how much does a logo cost?\n\nThe honest answer is that it depends — but not in the vague way that sounds. There are real, specific factors that move the price up or down, and once you understand them, the range of quotes you have probably already seen online will make a lot more sense.\n\n## Why Logo Prices Vary So Much\n\nYou can find someone on Fiverr offering a logo for ₦5,000, and a branding studio quoting ₦500,000 for the same word — logo. They are not actually selling the same thing.\n\nA ₦5,000 logo is usually a quick template edit, sometimes built in five minutes using stock icon packs. There is no research, no strategy, no consideration of how it will look on your packaging, your signage, or your Instagram grid. It gets you something to put on your page today, but it rarely holds up as your business grows.\n\nA properly priced logo project, on the other hand, includes time spent understanding your business, sketching multiple concepts, refining the strongest direction, and testing it across real use cases before you ever see a final file.\n\n## What Actually Affects the Price\n\n**The depth of the process.** A logo built from a 10-minute brief costs less than one built from a full discovery conversation about your business, competitors, and audience. More thinking time means a higher price, and usually a stronger result.\n\n**How many concepts you see.** Some designers show you one direction. Others show two or three distinct concepts before narrowing down. More concepts mean more design hours.\n\n**What you get at the end.** A logo delivered as a single PNG file is a different deliverable from a full package — vector files, color variations, a black-and-white version, and usage guidelines. The second one costs more because it is genuinely more work, and it is the version that actually protects you later.\n\n**Revisions included.** Unlimited revisions sound great until you realize they often lead to an endless back-and-forth that never quite finishes. A clear number of revision rounds, built into the price, usually leads to a better and faster outcome for everyone.\n\n## A Realistic Range\n\nFor a properly considered logo — one with a real process behind it, delivered with the file types and variations you will actually need — expect a project to fall somewhere in the range of ₦80,000 to ₦350,000 in the Lagos market, depending on the designer\'s experience and exactly what is included. Anything significantly below that is almost always a template, not a custom design process. Anything well above it usually includes a fuller brand identity system, not just a logo mark.\n\n## The Real Question to Ask\n\nInstead of asking "how much does a logo cost," a more useful question is: "what am I actually getting for this price?" A cheap logo with no real process behind it is not actually cheap if you end up paying again in a year because it never looked right anywhere outside the one file you were given.\n\nIf you are budgeting for a logo or full brand identity and want a clear quote based on exactly what you need, that is a conversation I am always happy to have before any commitment.',
  'business',
  true,
  NOW() - INTERVAL '2 days',
  'Logo Design Pricing in Lagos: What to Actually Expect — Nicopixel',
  'Confused by logo design prices in Lagos? Here is an honest breakdown of what actually affects cost and a realistic price range to expect.'
),
(
  'Designing for Events: What Most People Forget Until It Is Too Late',
  'designing-for-events-what-people-forget',
  'Event design is not just a flyer. Here is what actually goes into designing for an event properly, and the details that get overlooked until the week it matters most.',
  E'When people think about event design, they usually picture one thing: a flyer. Maybe a nice Instagram post announcing the date. That is part of it, but it is the smallest part — and it is almost never the piece that determines whether an event actually feels put-together on the day.\n\nHere is what proper event design actually involves, and the parts that tend to get forgotten until the week of the event, when it is too late to fix them properly.\n\n## It Starts Before the Announcement\n\nGood event design begins with a visual direction — colors, type, a consistent look — decided before a single flyer goes out. Without this, every piece of communication for the event ends up looking like it came from a different event entirely. The save-the-date looks nothing like the final flyer, which looks nothing like the signage on the day.\n\nA defined visual direction means anyone seeing any piece of communication — flyer, invite, banner, program card — instantly recognizes it as part of the same event, even before they read a single word.\n\n## The Pieces People Forget\n\n**Signage and wayfinding.** A flyer announces the event. Signage helps people once they arrive — where to check in, where the restrooms are, which direction the main hall is. Events without this end up with confused guests and a lot of repeated questions to ushers.\n\n**Print-ready files, not just screen files.** A flyer that looks great on Instagram can look completely different printed on a banner, because screen colors and print colors do not always match, and resolution that looks sharp on a phone can look blurry blown up to banner size. Files need to be prepared specifically for how they will actually be used.\n\n**A program or run-of-show design.** For more structured events — conferences, weddings, formal programs — a printed or digital program that guests can actually follow adds a level of polish that is immediately noticeable, and its absence is just as noticeable.\n\n**Backdrop and stage design.** This is often where the biggest visual impression is made, since it is what ends up in every photo from the event. A backdrop designed as an afterthought shows up in every single photo afterward.\n\n## Why This Gets Missed\n\nMost of the planning energy for an event goes into logistics — venue, catering, guest list — and design gets treated as a final, rushed step. The flyer goes out, and everything else gets handled "closer to the date." By the time anyone thinks about signage or a backdrop, there is no time left to design something considered, only time to grab whatever is fastest.\n\n## Designing It as One System\n\nThe events that feel the most professional are the ones where every visual piece — flyer, signage, backdrop, program — was designed together, as one connected system, rather than as separate last-minute tasks handled by whoever was available that week.\n\nIf you are planning an event and want the visual side handled as a complete system rather than a rushed flyer, that is exactly the kind of project worth bringing in a designer for early — not the week before.',
  'events',
  true,
  NOW() - INTERVAL '5 days',
  'Designing for Events: What Most People Forget — Nicopixel',
  'Event design is more than a flyer. Learn what actually goes into proper event design and the details most people overlook until it is too late.'
)
ON CONFLICT (slug) DO NOTHING;
